    "109702795": {
      "title": "Ultra-fine feature printed circuits and multi-chip Modules",
      "abstract": "Abstract As semiconductor devices evolve, so do the packages that house them and the printed circuit boards (PCBs) that support and interconnect them to form systems. The higher numbers of connections per device are squeezed into smaller pitches, both on the package and in the PCB, to fit into the available space and to improve electrical performance. Ultimately, individual packages are not required for each device. This paper describes substrates available from GEC-Marconi suitable for carrying and interconnecting packaged or unpackaged devices, or a combination of them, manufactured using techniques and materials familiar to the PCB industry. Multi-chip modules using lamination techniques to make the substrates (MCM-Ls) are a natural extension of printed circuit technology to meet the ever increasing demands of system integration and density. As with other forms of multi-chip module (MCM), the interconnection density is so high that most circuits need very few signal layers — often only two. The substrate can also incorporate layers to control thermal expansion and extract heat. MCM-L substrates are extraordinarily versatile; they can accommodate packaged ICs (for example, fine-pitch surface mount technology), unpackaged ICs, other MCMs, and odd-form components. These ultra-fine feature substrates can provide solutions for a wide range of sizes, complexities, performance and market sectors at competitive prices."
    },
    "107715963": {
      "title": "Evaluation of reliability of µBGA solder joints through twisting and bending",
      "abstract": "The paper describes a study on the solder joint mechanical reliability evaluation of two Grid Arra packages; a micro Land Grid Array (μLGA) and a micro Ball Grid Array (μBGA) planned to be used on mobile phones. uBGA modules are subjected to a series of qualifications tests by the vendors but not solder joints. The μGA packages considered in this paper are at early development stages and significant improvements are expected. In the study daisy chain μBGAS were used which allows to monitor the electrical continuity of the modules. The study evaluates whether solder joints can stand mechanical stresses induced on PCBs during the assembly and in normal use. Stresses induced in phone assembly process would include few presses and twists while in normal use can include; thermal stresses during use in indoor and outdoor and mechanical stress in keypad pressing, carrying phones in (tight) jeans pockets, accidentally dropping phones, etc. The mechanical tests included cyclic twisting and bending PCBs with μBGA solder joints to failure, while continuously monitoring electrical continuity. Weibull model was used to analyze cycles to failure test data. Results indicate that it is most unlikely anticipate μBGA solder joint failures in normal use. Solder joint failures were analyzed by micro sectioning and x-raying. Failure analysis, revealed as expected, that these are mainly due to fatigue. It is recommended to continue tests with more representative updated packages."
    }
  },
